'''Naomi Gleit''' is vice-president of social good and Senior Director of the Growth, Engagement, and Mobile Team at [[Facebook]].<ref name=latimes-profile>{{cite web|url = http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/22/business/la-fi-himi-gleit-20121223|title = Naomi Gleit helps keep Facebook growing. The senior director of Facebook's growth, engagement and mobile team has seen the social network grow to more than 1 billion users today from 1 million in 2005.|date = December 22, 2012|accessdate = July 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''}}</ref><ref name=fastcompany-growth>{{cite web|url = https://www.fastcompany.com/40432085/how-facebooks-growth-team-used-science-and-empathy-to-reach-two-billion-users|title = How Facebook Used Science And Empathy To Reach Two Billion Users. Facebook’s growth team has a methodical approach to understanding what new users want, and a surprisingly broad mandate.|date = June 27, 2017|accessdate = July 9, 2017|publisher = ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]''}}</ref><ref name=dame-profile>{{cite web|url = https://www.damemagazine.com/2012/05/17/made-women-facebook-0|title = The Made Women of Facebook. Five women who are going to have a hell of a weekend.|publisher = DAME|last = Nishi|first = Dennis|accessdate = July 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=marieclaire-interview>{{cite web|url = http://www.marieclaire.com/career-advice/news/a22360/facebook-and-gucci-mission-to-makeover-the-world/|title = Inside Facebook's Big Plans for the Future. VP of Social Good Naomi Gleit on the company's mission to make over the world.|last = Blaha|first = Jenna|date = September 2, 2016|accessdate = July 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[Marie Claire]]''}}</ref> She has been identified as Facebook's longest-serving employee after CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]], having been at the company from July 18, 2005 to the present.<ref name=latimes-profile/><ref name=gleit-adweek>{{cite web|url = http://www.adweek.com/digital/los-angeles-times-profiles-naomi-gleit/|title = ‘Los Angeles Times’ Profiles Naomi Gleit, Second-Most-Tenured Facebook Employee. It’s no surprise that Facebook Co-Founder and CEO Mark Zuckerberg has the most tenure of anyone at the social network, but who comes in second on that list? The Los Angeles Times profiled the answer to that question: Senior Director of the Growth, Engagement, and Mobile Team Naomi Gleit.|date = December 26, 2012|accessdate = July 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[Adweek]]''}}</ref><ref name=bi-early-facebook-employees>{{cite web|url = http://www.businessinsider.com/early-facebook-employees-2015-5/|title = WHERE ARE THEY NOW: Meet Facebook's first 20 employees|last = Shontell|first = Alyssa|last2 = Kosoff|first2 = Maya|date = May 30, 2015|accessdate = July 23, 2017}}</ref>

== Early life and education ==

Gleit was born to a "[[tiger mom]]" who ferried her to ballet, piano, karate and Chinese lessons, and a Jewish father an immigration lawyer who took her to Hebrew school.<ref name=latimes-profile/>

Gleit majored in Science, Technology, and Society at [[Stanford University]], where she wrote her senior thesis on Facebook, and how it beat out rival social networking service Club Nexus at Stanford University (the creator of Club Nexus would later go on to create [[Orkut]]).<ref name=latimes-profile/><ref name=leanin>{{cite web|url = https://leanin.org/stories/naomi-gleit/|title = Naomi Gleit: Product Manager, Growth|accessdate = July 23, 2017|publisher = Lean In}}</ref>

== Career ==

Gleit has spent her entire career at Facebook.<ref name=bi-early-facebook-employees/><ref name=fastcompany-growth/>

=== Marketing and growth team ===

After writing her senior thesis about Facebook, Gleit was bullish on Facebook's potential and applied to work there. She began work as a marketing associate<ref name=bi-early-facebook-employees/> on July 18, 2005, which was also her birthday. She came on board shortly after the company had hit 1 million users.<ref name=latimes-profile/> In her role, Gleit promoted Facebook beyond colleges and to high schools, facilitating the eventual opening up of Facebook to all users.<ref name=latimes-profile/> In 2007, Zuckerberg asked Gleit to become a product manager for the growth team, and she accepted.<ref name=latimes-profile/> The growth team was led by [[Chamath Palihapitiya]].<ref name=fastcompany-growth/> In 2009, Gleit, describing her job to ''[[Newsweek]]'', said "My job isn't done until literally everyone in the world is on the site."<ref name=newsweek-gleit>{{cite web|url = http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2009/07/21/facebook-at-age-five.html|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20110912231549/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2009/07/21/facebook-at-age-five.html|archivedate = September 12, 2011|title = Facebook at Age Five|date = July 21, 2009|accessdate = July 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[Newsweek]]''}}</ref>

=== Facebook Safety Check ===

Gleit was part of the team that worked on and released [[Facebook Safety Check]] in 2014, inspired by people's use of social media to connect with friends and family in the wake of the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami]].<ref name=fastcompany-growth/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.fb.com/news/2014/10/introducing-safety-check|title = Introducing Safety Check|publisher = Facebook|date = October 15, 2014|accessdate = April 27, 2015|last = Gleit|first = Naomi|last2 = Zeng|first2 = Sharon|last3 = Cottle|first3 = Peter}}</ref><ref name=wired-fsc>{{cite web|url = https://www.wired.com/2016/11/facebook-disaster-response/|title = How Facebook Is Transforming Disaster Response|date = November 10, 2016|accessdate = July 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''}}</ref> Putting this initiative in a broader context, Gleit later told ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'': "[Zuckerberg] wants us to take this data-driven, product-driven approach and apply that to other problems because it’s not unique, per se, to growth".<ref name=fastcompany-growth/> Gleit continues to be in charge of Facebook Safety Check.<ref name=fastcompany-growth/>

=== Social good team, including Fundraisers and other initiatives ===

At the Social Good Summit in New York City on September 27, 2015, Gleit announced that Facebook was creating a team dedicated to social good.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://mashable.com/2015/09/27/facebook-social-good-team/#iDgUrxDTbEqY|title = Facebook looks to assert itself as a force for social good|last = Figerman|first = Seth|date = September 27, 2015|accessdate = July 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[Mashable]]''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.businessadministrationinformation.com/news/facebook-social-good-team|title = Facebook Now Has a Team Dedicated to Social Good|last = Thurston|first = Susan|date = October 8, 2015|accessdate = July 23, 2017|publisher = Business Administration Information}}</ref> Gleit's title would change to vice-president for social good.<ref name=fastcompany-growth/><ref name=wired-fsc/>

Under Gleit's leadership, Facebook, in 2016 and 2017, rolled out support for Fundraisers, including nonprofits fundraising for themselves, as well as individuals setting up fundraisers for personal causes and nonprofits they want to support.<ref name=fastcompany-growth/><ref>{{cite web|url = https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/30/facebook-introduces-personal-fundraising-tools-donate-buttons-in-facebook-live/|title = Facebook introduces personal fundraising tools, donate buttons in Facebook Live for Pages|last = Perez|first = Sarah|date = March 30, 2017|accessdate = July 18, 2017|publisher = ''TechCrunch''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://mashable.com/2017/03/30/facebook-personal-fundraisers/#c7cKUaNiMmqa|title = Facebook's fundraisers now help you raise money for yourself and friends|last = Petronzio|first = Matt|date = March 30, 2017|accessdate = July 18, 2017|publisher = ''TechCrunch''}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/30/facebook-gofundme-feature-to-accept-donations-personal-fundraiser.html|title = Facebook moves into crowdfunding for emergencies|last = Balakrishnan|first = Anita|date = March 30, 2017|accessdate = July 18, 2017|publisher = CNBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/24/facebooks-personal-fundraisers-exit-beta-now-support-raising-money-for-sports-teams-communities/|title = Facebook’s personal fundraisers exit beta, now support raising money for sports teams & communities|last = Perez|first = Sarah|date = May 24, 2017|accessdate = July 18, 2017|publisher = ''TechCrunch''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://newsroom.fb.com/news/2017/05/expanding-facebook-fundraisers-to-more-people-and-causes/|title = Expanding Facebook Fundraisers to More People and Causes|last = Gleit|first = Naomi|date = May 24, 2017|accessdate = July 18, 2017|publisher = Facebook}}</ref>

